    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-17T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-17T03:00:00-05:00" n="500"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d500">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker, Charles</persName>/35: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1" type="from">Adams</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-17T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 17, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>43. 1. The Chinese naval vessels which have been in communication with <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s captors since late February
                    are apparently accomplishing nothing through negotiation toward his release. The
                    latest demand of the bandits is the payment of silver dollars 40,000 for
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release. Money is
                    not available from private sources for the payment of further ransom and it
                    would, therefore, appear that the employment of force offers the only chance of
                    obtaining <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s early
                    release unless Chinese Government can be induced to pay <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s ransom in accordance with
                    precedents afforded by the Perdicaris case<note n="19" xml:id="d500fn19">See
                            <ref target="frus1904#pg_307">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1904, pp. 307</ref>, <ref
                            target="frus1904#pg_338">338</ref>, <ref target="frus1904#pg_496"
                            >496</ref> ff.</note> reported on page 807, volume 6, <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_MF1">Moore</persName>’s <hi rend="italic"
                        >International Law Digest</hi>, and by the Lincheng case.<note n="20"
                        xml:id="d500fn20">See <ref target="frus1923v01#pg_631">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., 1923, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>,
                            pp. 631</ref> ff.</note> The Hupeh authorities are desperately short of
                    funds and it would be idle to hope that they would be persuaded to pay
                    ransom.</p>
                <p>2. The general military attacks against <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker</persName>’s captors would not assist towards his release and I can
                    only suggest that a lever with which to force his release would be obtained by
                    the taking of hostages at Pailochi. I reported in my number 34 of February 20,
                        <pb facs="0580" n="482" xml:id="pg_482"/> 1 p.m., that I had made this
                    suggestion to General <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_HC1">Ho
                        Chen-chun</persName> and that he had considered it to be practicable.</p>
                <p>3. I am again urging General <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_HC1">Ho
                        Chen-chun</persName> to procure hostages at Pailochi but I doubt his ability
                    to do so by means of troops. It seems obvious that a naval operation would have
                    been [<hi rend="italic">big?</hi>] chance of success through surprise. I
                    understand that <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_HC1">Ho Chen-chun</persName>
                    has not authority over the Navy. It is possible that if the Legation were to
                    approach other Chinese authorities than the Foreign Office, the Chinese Navy
                    might be induced to undertake a surprise raid upon Pailochi with the object of
                    obtaining hostages. My suggestion would be that General <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_CK3">Chiang Kai-shih</persName> be urged to order
                    such action or, if he cannot be reached, that representations be made direct to
                    the Minister of the Navy.</p>
                <p>4. If the above suggestion cannot be carried out I shall be grateful for any
                    suggestion as to further action in the case.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Adams</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
